00:00:22.630 --> 00:00:23.930
&gt;&gt; Roberta I.

00:00:23.930 --> 00:00:25.230
Shaffer: Good evening, my
name is Roberta Shaffer,

00:00:25.230 --> 00:00:27.680
and I have the absolute
pleasure of serving

00:00:27.680 --> 00:00:31.350
as the 24th Law Librarian
of Congress.

00:00:31.350 --> 00:00:34.820
Tonight is a particularly
exciting evening for me,

00:00:34.820 --> 00:00:40.370
because it represents the really
bringing to fruition a discussion

00:00:40.370 --> 00:00:44.800
and a dream that Rob Casper
and I had about five years ago,

00:00:44.800 --> 00:00:50.480
about somehow marrying law and
poetry; law and literature.

00:00:50.480 --> 00:00:54.400 position:56%
And my dream at the time -- although
I never shared this with Rob

00:00:54.400 --> 00:00:59.950 position:56%
or my cartoon balloon at the time --
was to totally redefine the concept

00:00:59.950 --> 00:01:01.250
of poetic justice [background
laughter].

00:01:01.250 --> 00:01:07.120
And so I hope that we will
be able to do that tonight.

00:01:07.120 --> 00:01:10.340
Because there is something
very, very important

00:01:10.340 --> 00:01:15.360
about the sibling relationship
between law and poetry.

00:01:15.360 --> 00:01:22.160
And in fact, Attica Locke, the 2016
recipient of the Harper Lee prize

00:01:22.160 --> 00:01:24.940
for fiction, has said that "Law

00:01:24.940 --> 00:01:29.410
and literature are
really fraternal twins."

00:01:29.410 --> 00:01:33.650
And surely we can see that
they share the womb of words

00:01:33.650 --> 00:01:37.820
in both an oral and
a written tradition.

00:01:37.820 --> 00:01:42.790
But law and poetry, and law and
literature find common ground

00:01:42.790 --> 00:01:45.540 position:56%
in their reliance upon storytelling.

00:01:45.540 --> 00:01:49.140
In their heavy use of
analogy and metaphor.

00:01:49.140 --> 00:01:53.450
In their conviction for form
and format, which they then love

00:01:53.450 --> 00:01:56.040
to take great liberties with.

00:01:56.040 --> 00:01:58.330
The reliance upon history
and precedent.

00:01:58.330 --> 00:02:02.470
And let's not forget
the heavy use of fiction

00:02:02.470 --> 00:02:04.620
in both disciplines
[background laughter].

00:02:04.620 --> 00:02:10.320
The immortal Shelly provides some
conformation in what I call an

00:02:10.320 --> 00:02:13.900
"Early amicus brief
to civilization".

00:02:13.900 --> 00:02:19.210
His 1821 defense of
poetry -- a legal term --

00:02:19.210 --> 00:02:25.570
calls poets the "unacknowledged
legislatures of the world".

00:02:25.570 --> 00:02:31.380
And in a more contemporary
setting, the poet and songwriter,

00:02:31.380 --> 00:02:35.740 position:56%
Leonard Cohen, who is now ultimately
legitimated by the Nobel Prize

00:02:35.740 --> 00:02:42.070
to Bob Dylan, calls poetry
"the evidence of life".

