00:25:49.050 --> 00:25:51.600
&gt;&gt; Martha Dragich:
Good evening everyone.

00:25:51.600 --> 00:25:56.180
My immediate task is to talk just a
little bit about law in literature.

00:25:56.180 --> 00:26:00.210
Responding to the question that may
be latent in many of your minds,

00:26:00.210 --> 00:26:01.890
what do the two have
to do with each other?

00:26:01.890 --> 00:26:04.480
Now Roberta talked about that some.

00:26:04.480 --> 00:26:10.450 position:56%
And I have to say, I will talk about
literature generally speaking rather

00:26:10.450 --> 00:26:13.510
than about poetry specifically,
because I am not qualified to talk

00:26:13.510 --> 00:26:16.860
about poetry specifically.

00:26:18.020 --> 00:26:22.950
So about 20 or 30 years ago,

00:26:22.950 --> 00:26:27.440
law schools started offering
courses in law and literature.

00:26:27.440 --> 00:26:33.400
There an amazing variety
of such courses.

00:26:33.400 --> 00:26:38.490
There is a literature of law and
literature that has developed.

00:26:38.490 --> 00:26:44.010
And it's hard to generalize much
about these courses in this field

00:26:44.010 --> 00:26:47.750
of study because they're
characterized most by variety.

00:26:47.750 --> 00:26:52.810
But I'll try to give you,
just in very brief form,

00:26:52.810 --> 00:26:56.900
a few of the objectives why
people offer such courses.

00:26:56.900 --> 00:27:00.200
Why people write about
law and literature.

00:27:00.200 --> 00:27:05.280
What do we think we -- either
field can learn from the other one,

00:27:05.280 --> 00:27:08.110
how do they correspond
with each other?

00:27:08.110 --> 00:27:12.930
And just by coincidence, I
read something the other day.

00:27:12.930 --> 00:27:17.640
I was reading a very new book of
essays by a poet, Mary Oliver.

00:27:17.640 --> 00:27:20.410
The collection of essays
is called, "Up Stream".

00:27:20.410 --> 00:27:25.760
And I read this sentence which
seemed to me quite pertinent.

00:27:25.760 --> 00:27:27.690
She says, "The best use

00:27:27.690 --> 00:27:32.820
of literature bends not toward
the narrow and absolute,

00:27:32.820 --> 00:27:35.410
but to the extravagant
and the possible."

00:27:35.410 --> 00:27:38.710
Well narrow and absolute sound
to me something like law.

00:27:38.710 --> 00:27:42.960
And extravagant and possible,
perhaps something like literature.

00:27:42.960 --> 00:27:46.050
And she goes on to say that
rather than providing answers --

00:27:46.050 --> 00:27:49.280
I'm paraphrasing now -- rather
than providing answers --

00:27:49.280 --> 00:27:54.280
Mary Oliver suggests -- literature
opens doors and tells us to look

00:27:54.280 --> 00:27:57.270
at things and think about
things for ourselves.

00:27:57.270 --> 00:28:03.790
So that, I think, encapsulates
perhaps the few strands

00:28:03.790 --> 00:28:08.700
that I'll talk about in the study
and teaching of law and literature.

00:28:08.700 --> 00:28:12.120
So these are some of the
most prominent objectives.

00:28:12.120 --> 00:28:14.940
One is to contextualize law

00:28:14.940 --> 00:28:18.010
and events triggering
the application of law.

00:28:18.010 --> 00:28:19.970 position:56%
A apelet opinion -- the way we teach

00:28:19.970 --> 00:28:22.480
in law schools is to
use apelet opinions.

00:28:22.480 --> 00:28:26.400
So the end of the line
-- the end of the story;

00:28:26.400 --> 00:28:29.340
after everything has
happened, much being --

00:28:29.340 --> 00:28:34.720
having been stripped out along the
way; condensed down to a narrow set

00:28:34.720 --> 00:28:39.240
of relevant facts and so forth.

00:28:39.240 --> 00:28:44.540
So law as delivered to law students

00:28:44.540 --> 00:28:51.140
and lawyers, is narrow
in that sense.

00:28:51.140 --> 00:28:53.630
It has a very narrow focus.

00:28:53.630 --> 00:28:56.650
Literature, on the other hand,
paints a much richer picture.

00:28:56.650 --> 00:29:05.410
It's full of the details of events
and lives and personalities;

00:29:05.410 --> 00:29:08.300
circumstances, motivations
and so forth.

00:29:08.300 --> 00:29:12.110
So finding a way to bring
some of this context back in,

00:29:12.110 --> 00:29:15.910
and to understand that regardless
of what the apelet opinion says

00:29:15.910 --> 00:29:19.240
in the end, that may be the
condensed version that's relevant

00:29:19.240 --> 00:29:21.150
to the rule of law
that's established,

00:29:21.150 --> 00:29:24.700
but earlier on there was
a lot more to the story.

00:29:24.700 --> 00:29:27.870
And it's important for
law students in particular

00:29:27.870 --> 00:29:29.330
to develop an understanding.

00:29:29.330 --> 00:29:31.370
Because they're going to be dealing
with real people who are coming

00:29:31.370 --> 00:29:34.670
in at the beginning of
this story with a whole set

00:29:34.670 --> 00:29:38.970
of life circumstances and hopes and
dreams and problems and what not.

00:29:38.970 --> 00:29:43.600
So building that context
back in is one objective.

00:29:43.600 --> 00:29:48.470
Another objective of the law
in literature movement --

00:29:48.470 --> 00:29:50.920
if you can call it that;
that's too strong a word.

00:29:50.920 --> 00:29:59.950
But law in literature does have
some early connection with law --

00:29:59.950 --> 00:30:02.140
with critical legal
studies; law in feminism.

00:30:02.140 --> 00:30:03.620
